Not too long after I was laid off, I found out I was pregnant. We were excited, yet terrified. How would we afford this on one income? I eventually did get a job, but making less than $7 an hour part time didn't do much at all. Our beautiful daughter came into the world on September 13, 2005. Soon after, we got a credit card to transfer some high interest balances and pay off our hospital bill.  For a while, things were okay. We weren't doing great, but we were surviving. Day by day, we sunk further into debt. And then the unthinkable happened- my husband was laid off. We both looked for jobs, but nothing came in for four months.  Another credit card entered the scene, which we essentially lived off of.  Excluding my looming student loans (I graduate in May), our current debt hovers around the $15,000 mark. My school schedule and my husband's work schedule finally allowed me to go back to work in August. Two incomes is better than one, but we're still struggling.  Getting a loan to consolidate everything would be a life saver. We're paying as high as 19% interest on one credit card. I am a good candidate for this loan because I own the mobile home park, and have for fourteen years.  We are in full control of this park since we own all of the homes there with the exception of one.  All of the homes, except for two, are free and clear.  I have an excellent credit history with 18 pages of paid as agreed.  There is one 30 day late pay that is an error on the lender's part and is being contested.  My fico score goes up and down, typically between 801 and 760.  Since there is no such thing as financing for non-owner occupied mobile and manufactured homes, we have had to use consumer credit in lieu of same.  This drives our fico score down even though our credit history shows hundred of thousands of dollars of loans being paid as agreed.  I have been a real estate investor for nearly 35 years, and I have an excellent track record of producing excellent products, nearly all of which have been keepers.  We rarely sell property.  We buy, then improve, then rent out our property.  Since we own other properties as well, we have lots of other rental income.  Our gross income greatly exceeds my professional income from the University.  Since the total rental income cannot be quickly and conveniently verified, then our debt to income ratio is a challenge to calculate.  Our actual debt to income is more like 50-55%.  We really keep our money working for us.  We are an excellent credit risk.  We always repay our loans.  We do a lot of rehab work, and so we are interested in establishing several private lending relationships.  There can be lots of repeat business from us.  We have several different projects, including projects where we are interested in borrowing much larger sums, which can be fully secured by real estate.  We have lots of real estate equity that we would like to put to work by using it as collateral for private lenders.  We are not interested in working with hard money lenders.  We very much prefer to work with individuals, people that perhaps do not currently wish to be in the stock market, nor with some of the larger banks.  We are hard working, honest, souls with excellent references.  Would you like to earn some good money in a safe and secure way.  Give us a try.....you will be pleased.  We do exactly what we say we will.  Trust, after all, is a TWO WAY STREET.  We are worthy of your trust.  Have a great day!!!.
